Are you calling `ModelLoader::_detect` in a loop? I'm not very familiar with the C++ API but I think you have some unnecessary operations in there. Example:
```
std::vector<const char*> inputNames{"input"};
std::vector<const char*> outputNames{"output"};
std::vector<Ort::Value> inputTensors;
Ort::MemoryInfo memoryInfo = Ort::MemoryInfo::CreateCpu(OrtAllocatorType::OrtArenaAllocator, OrtMemType::OrtMemTypeDefault);
```
These lines never change so why re-initialize them on each iteration (especially the Ort::MemoryInfo::CreateCPU() call)?

Also, assuming your image dimensions arent't changing, you can also initialize those lines only once:

```
std::vector<int64_t> inputDimsInFact{ batchSize, 3, imgH, imgW };
size_t inputTensorSize = vectorProduct(inputDimsInFact);
std::vector<float> inputTensorValues(inputTensorSize);
```

This way your detect method will simply overwrite data on existing memory.
Again, I'm not very familiar with the C++ API so correct me if I'm wrong there.
As for your problem, I'd say use a timer to check the `session->Run()` operation alone and see if it is slower when there's a slight pause between its calls.

